{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17597939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17597939"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15434"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15434"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.39,0.33,0.07,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69802"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8125"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19702"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69802"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPathogenic strains of \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E can cause various types of gastroenteritis through different virulence mechanisms. Some strains produce toxins that can cause systemic complications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathotypes of E. coli produces verotoxin and is associated with glomerular thrombosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enteropathogenic E. coli","Enterotoxigenic E. coli","Enterohemorrhagic E. coli","Enteroinvasive E. coli","Enteroaggregative E. coli"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003EEnterohemorrhagic E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E (EHEC). This pathotype produces Shiga-like toxin (verotoxin) which damages endothelial cells, leading to fibrin thrombi formation in glomerular capillaries. This process can result in haemolytic uraemic syndrome, characterised by microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopaenia and acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other pathotypes have different mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteropathogenic E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E causes attaching and effacing lesions in the intestinal epithelium\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterotoxigenic E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E produces heat-labile and heat-stable toxins causing secretory diarrhoea\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteroinvasive E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E directly invades and destroys intestinal epithelial cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnteroaggregative E. coli\u003C/strong\u003E adheres to intestinal mucosa in a characteristic \u0027stacked brick\u0027 pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Enterohemorrhagic Escherichia coli (EHEC) produces Shiga-like toxin (verotoxin) which can cause haemolytic uraemic syndrome.","Verotoxin damages endothelial cells leading to fibrin thrombi formation in glomerular capillaries.","Different E. coli pathotypes have distinct virulence mechanisms and clinical presentations."],"references":["Mueller M, Tainter CR. Escherichia coli Infection. [Updated 2023 Jul 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564298/","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338","Burd EM, Hinrichs BH. Gastrointestinal Infections. Molecular Pathology in Clinical Practice. 2015 May 19:707\u201334. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-19674-9_50. PMCID: PMC7123654","Kotloff KL. Bacterial diarrhoea. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2022 Apr 1;34(2):147-155. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0000000000001107. PMID: 35165210","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15434"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T19:49:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T19:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8125"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69802"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null